Certainly! Below is an example of how you can achieve a responsive full-width background image with an overlaid widget containing text limited to 75% of the screen width. This example uses HTML and CSS, which you can integrate into your custom WordPress theme.

### HTML Structure

```html
<!-- Landing Section -->
<section class="landing-section">
  <div class="overlay-widget">
    <h1>Your Catchy Headline</h1>
    <p>Your engaging introductory text goes here. It can span multiple lines and will be constrained to 75% of the screen width for better readability.</p>
  </div>
</section>
```

### CSS Styling

```css
/* Ensure the body and html take full height */
html, body {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  height: 100%;
}

/* Landing Section Styling */
.landing-section {
  position: relative; /* Establishes a positioning context for the overlay */
  width: 100%;
  /* Using aspect-ratio to maintain the desired height based on width */
  aspect-ratio: 16 / 9; /* Adjust the ratio as needed */
  background-image: url('path-to-your-image.jpg'); /* Replace with your image path */
  background-size: cover; /* Ensures the image covers the entire section */
  background-position: center; /* Centers the image */
  background-repeat: no-repeat; /* Prevents the image from repeating */
}

/* Overlay Widget Styling */
.overlay-widget {
  position: absolute; /* Positions the widget relative to the landing section */
  top: 50%; /* Vertically centers the widget */
  left: 50%; /* Horizontally centers the widget */
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%); /* Adjusts the position to exact center */
  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5); /* Semi-transparent background for better text readability */
  color: #fff; /* Text color */
  padding: 20px;
  max-width: 75%; /* Limits the widget's width to 75% of the screen */
  box-sizing: border-box; /* Ensures padding is included in the width */
  border-radius: 8px; /* Optional: Adds rounded corners */
  text-align: center; /* Centers the text inside the widget */
}

/* Responsive Typography (Optional) */
.overlay-widget h1 {
  font-size: 2em;
  margin-bottom: 0.5em;
}

.overlay-widget p {
  font-size: 1.2em;
}

/* Media Queries for Smaller Screens (Optional) */
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .overlay-widget {
    max-width: 90%;
    padding: 15px;
  }

  .overlay-widget h1 {
    font-size: 1.5em;
  }

  .overlay-widget p {
    font-size: 1em;
  }
}
```

### Explanation

1. **HTML Structure**:
   - The `<section>` element with the class `landing-section` serves as the container for your landing page section.
   - Inside this section, a `<div>` with the class `overlay-widget` contains the text content you want to display over the background image.

2. **CSS Styling**:
   - **`.landing-section`**:
     - `position: relative;` establishes a positioning context for absolutely positioned child elements.
     - `width: 100%;` ensures the section spans the full width of the viewport.
     - `aspect-ratio: 16 / 9;` maintains the aspect ratio of the section. You can adjust this to match your desired image aspect ratio.
     - `background-image`, `background-size`, `background-position`, and `background-repeat` handle the responsive background image.

   - **`.overlay-widget`**:
     - `position: absolute;`, `top: 50%;`, `left: 50%;`, and `transform: translate(-50%, -50%);` center the widget both vertically and horizontally within the section.
     - `background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);` adds a semi-transparent background to improve text readability against the image.
     - `max-width: 75%;` restricts the widget's width to 75% of the viewport, ensuring it doesn't become too wide on large screens.
     - Additional styles like `padding`, `border-radius`, and `text-align` enhance the appearance.

   - **Responsive Typography and Media Queries**:
     - The optional responsive typography ensures that text remains readable on various screen sizes.
     - Media queries adjust the widget's max-width and padding for smaller screens, improving mobile responsiveness.

### Integration with WordPress

To integrate this into your WordPress theme:

1. **Add the HTML to Your Template**:
   - Depending on where you want this section, you might add the HTML to a specific template file (e.g., `front-page.php` for the homepage) or use a custom page template.

2. **Enqueue the CSS**:
   - Add the CSS to your theme's stylesheet (`style.css`) or enqueue a separate CSS file in your `functions.php`:

     ```php
     function custom_theme_styles() {
       wp_enqueue_style( 'landing-section-style', get_template_directory_uri() . '/css/landing-section.css' );
     }
     add_action( 'wp_enqueue_scripts', 'custom_theme_styles' );
     ```

3. **Dynamic Background Image (Optional)**:
   - If you want the background image to be dynamic (e.g., set via the WordPress Customizer), you can use inline styles or add a custom field. Here's an example using inline styles with PHP:

     ```php
     <section class="landing-section" style="background-image: url('<?php echo esc_url( get_theme_mod('landing_background_image') ); ?>');">
       <!-- Overlay Widget -->
     </section>
     ```

     Ensure you've set up the corresponding setting in the Customizer to upload the background image.

### Final Notes

- **Accessibility**: Ensure that the text has sufficient contrast against the background for readability and accessibility.
- **Performance**: Optimize your background image for web use to ensure quick loading times.
- **Browser Support**: The `aspect-ratio` property is widely supported in modern browsers. If you need to support older browsers, consider using the padding-top hack to maintain aspect ratio.

By following this example, you should have a responsive landing page section with a full-width background image and a neatly overlaid text widget that maintains its proportions across different screen sizes.

